l Italy. Together, the contributors present a new critique of power that sustained both kingship and locally based elite networks throughout the Italian peninsula. A broad temporal range, covering the sixth to the twelfth century, allows this book to cross a number of ‘traditional’ fault-lines in Italian historiography – 774, 888, 962 and 1025. The essays provide wide-ranging analysis of the role of conflict in the period, the operation of power and the development of communal consciousness and collective action by protagonists and groups. It is thus essential reading for scholars, students and general readers who wish to understand the situation on the ground in the medieval Italian environment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aViolencezItalyxHistory. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aMedieval Studies. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Italy.2bisacsh  aMedieval Italy, Early Middle Ages, Social History, Conflict, Power, Violence.1 aBalzaretti, Ross, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarritt, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerndt, Guido M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorri, Francesco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeath, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeath, Christopher, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHoughton, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoughton, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aManarini, Edoardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNash, Penelope, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVeneziani, Enr